#### Perfect Tender Rule (Rule § 2-601)
The perfect tender rule under UCC Article 2 states that if the goods or delivery fail in any respect, the buyer may reject them entirely, accept them despite defects, or accept only part of the delivery. This can be strict, as even minor defects could potentially lead to rejection.

:p What is the Perfect Tender Rule?
??x
The perfect tender rule under UCC Article 2 allows the buyer to reject the goods if they fail in any respect, including minor defects such as a few minutes late. The rule emphasizes that only a "perfect tender" would create a condition for the buyer's obligation to accept and pay.

For instance:
- If you receive goods late but suffer no loss due to the delay.
- If you reject the goods because they cost more than current market prices despite being delivered on time, courts might find this not in good faith.

:p What is an example of how a court might interpret the Perfect Tender Rule?
??x
Courts often interpret the perfect tender rule with flexibility. For instance, if you receive goods late but suffer no loss due to the delay and reject them only because they cost more than market prices, courts are likely to find that your rejection was not in good faith.

Example:
```java
// Example code snippet for understanding delayed delivery impact
public class DeliveryStatus {
    private boolean deliveredOnTime;
    private double contractPrice;
    private double marketPrice;

    public void checkForGoodFaithRejection() {
        if (!deliveredOnTime) { // Goods are late
            return; // Assume no loss due to delay
        }
        if (contractPrice > marketPrice) { // Price is higher than market
            System.out.println("Reject in good faith: Price not justified.");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Rejection might be in bad faith.");
        }
    }
}
```

