#### Restitution in Contract Law

Restitution involves requiring a party who has been unjustly enriched at another's expense to return the benefit received. This remedy is particularly useful when partial performance leads to nonpayment under the contract.

:p In what situation might restitution be applicable in contract law?
??x
Restitution can be applied when one party has conferred a substantial benefit on the other party, but that benefit was not fully compensated due to a failure to substantially perform or other reasons. For example, if a contractor builds 80% of a project and the owner fails to pay, the contractor can claim restitution for the value of the work performed.

Restitution involves calculating the value of the benefit conferred (the completed portion of the project) and requiring the enriched party (owner in this case) to return that value. The key here is that even if there has been a breach by one party, restitution may still be sought as long as it does not prejudice the breaching party.

```java
public class RestitutionExample {
    private double projectValue;
    private double completedWorkPercentage;

    public void calculateRestitution() {
        double completedValue = projectValue * (completedWorkPercentage / 100);
        System.out.println("The contractor is entitled to: " + completedValue);
    }
}
```
