#### Limitation of Consequential Damages in Consumer Goods
Background context: Under UCC § 2-719(3), sellers can generally limit their liability to direct damages and disclaim responsibility for consequential damages. However, there is an exception where the limitation of such damages for personal injury related to consumer goods is considered unconscionable.
:p How does UCC § 2-719(3) affect a tire seller's ability to limit its liability?
??x
UCC § 2-719(3) states that a provision disclaiming liability for consequential damages resulting from personal injury in the case of consumer goods is prima facie unconscionable. This means that such a disclaimer is generally invalid if the sold item (in this case, tires) could cause personal injury.
For example:
- If a tire seller sells to a truck driver, it can disclaim liability for consequential damages related to property damage but cannot exclude liability for personal injury.
- If the tire seller sells to a commuter, it might have more flexibility in disclaiming all consequential damages, including those for personal injury.
```java
public class TireSeller {
    public void sellTire(Customer customer) {
        if (customer.isTruckDriver()) {
            // Can limit liability to direct and property damage only
            System.out.println("Limitation of liability applies.");
        } else if (customer.isCommuter()) {
            // More flexibility in disclaiming all consequential damages
            System.out.println("Can include a broader disclaimer for personal injury.");
        }
    }
}
```
